<p><b>Brahma</b> is the <a href="/wiki/Hinduism" title="Hinduism">Hindu</a> god (<a href="/wiki/Deva_(Hinduism)" title="Deva (Hinduism)">deva</a>) of creation and one of the <a href="/wiki/Trimurti" title="Trimurti">Trimurti</a>, the others being <a href="/wiki/Vishnu" title="Vishnu">Vishnu</a> and <a href="/wiki/Shiva" title="Shiva">Shiva</a>. He is not to be confused with the Supreme Cosmic Spirit in Hindu <a href="/wiki/Vedanta" title="Vedanta">Vedanta</a> philosophy known as <a href="/wiki/Brahman" title="Brahman">Brahman</a>. Brahmā's consort is <a href="/wiki/Saraswati" title="Saraswati">Saraswati</a>, the goddess of learning. Brahmā is often identified with <a href="/wiki/Prajapati" title="Prajapati">Prajapati</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Veda" title="Veda" class="mw-redirect">Vedic</a> deity.</p>
